I'm not sure what you're asking. See [distutils.command.install](https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/master/Lib/distutils/command/install.py#L22-L65) for the structures that distutils (and thus Setuptools) use as a basis for determining where to install scripts on a given platform.

@emmanuelle , What will take space is the `marker_locations` array, but if the volume size is more than 1290\*\*3 (and it's not extremely big nowadays), there *may* be greater marker locations than `int32` can handle.
`marker_locations` is only as big as how many markers there are. So let's take the very extreme theoretical scenario: there are 2**31-1 markers continuously, and none afterwards. In this case, using `int64` array will cause an unneeded increase of only 64 GB of RAM. And that's the maximal wasted RAM possible. Most likely it will never go near that. Just one marker after that - and it's already not a waste, cause 64-bit is needed.
One can test if 64-bit is needed, and make separate functions for 32-bit and 64-bit watershed, but it's a lot of added complexity to save a little RAM. Also, if there's not enough RAM for the 64-bit version, even the 32-bit version will not work, because `np.flatnonzero` returns an `int64` array anyway. My change just avoids its conversion to `int32`.

